  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970, US)\n- First international efforts to address financial crimes\n- Limited scope and enforcement mechanisms\n\n2. Key Milestones\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Increased international cooperation\n- Development of standardized anti-money laundering (AML) guidelines\n\n3. Major Legislative Developments\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Enhanced reporting requirements\n- Expanded definition of money laundering\n- Stricter penalties for financial institutions\n\n4. Recent Trends\n- Enhanced customer due diligence requirements\n- Cryptocurrency and digital asset regulations\n- Beneficial ownership transparency\n- Increased focus on technology-enabled monitoring\n\n5. Global Regulatory Framework\n- Comprehensive international standards\n- Risk-based approach to AML compliance\n- Systematic reporting of suspicious transactions\n- Cross-border information sharing\n\n6. Emerging Focus Areas\n- Cybercrime prevention\n- Complex financial technology regulations\n- Enhanced artificial intelligence and machine learning in detection\n- Blockchain and cryptocurrency tracking\n\nThe legislative landscape continues to evolve, becoming more sophisticated and comprehensive.",
